     1	# SQLAlchemy 2 Cutover
     2	
     3	This cutover removes helper-owned commits and moves transaction ownership to the
     4	API, worker, and admin command surfaces. Repository access now uses
     5	SQLAlchemy 2-style `select()` execution so callers can control one transaction
     6	per unit of work and get predictable rollback behavior.
     7	
     8	## Operator Expectations
     9	
    10	- API writes should run inside an explicit request-scoped transaction. Reads may
    11	  use a plain session, but they must not rely on repository helpers to commit or
    12	  close work implicitly.
    13	- Worker settlement retries are now atomic per call. If settlement fails after a
    14	  row is marked `processing`, the worker transaction rolls back and the entry
    15	  returns to its pre-run state.
    16	- Admin dry runs are read-only by design. Planning or reconciliation commands
    17	  may stage status changes in memory, but they must always roll back before the
    18	  command returns when `dry_run=True`.
    19	
    20	## Rollback Playbook
    21	
    22	1. Stop new worker or admin invocations if operators observe unexpected status
    23	   transitions during cutover.
    24	2. Re-run the failed worker or admin command only after confirming the previous
    25	   attempt rolled back and entries remain in their pre-command state.
    26	3. If a non-dry-run batch fails, expect the whole transaction to roll back; do
    27	   not manually repair partially queued or partially settled rows because the
    28	   cutover no longer commits mid-batch.
    29	
    30	Do not restore a legacy compatibility shim as a mitigation. The release gate for
    31	this cutover depends on dry-run safety and failure-time rollback semantics.

